review_blob: Aroma: heavy skunk. Nice pale gold color, with a light, quickly-disappearing head. At the first sip, I was surprised to find this tasted like real beer... not great beer, but beer nonetheless. Then came the cloyingly sweet aftertaste, which contrasted completely with my initial impression and seemed very unpleasant to me. As an accompaniment to pizza or strongly-flavored food, its OK. But after Id finished all my Clausthalers, I found a two-year-old bottle of Cusquea hidden in the back of my fridge, and (I shudder to admit) enjoyed drinking *that* a good deal more.

I had fond memories of this from drinking it in Indian restaurants years ago. Boy, was I disappointed to try it again. Aroma suggested bread to me at first, with citrus following... no skunkiness. Color is pale yellow, with no credible attempt at a head. Taste and mouth-feel? Ugh. Flat and industrial. OK to wash down strong Indian food, but on its own I had to force myself to finish it.

Lovely red-brown color with a firm white head that dissipates quickly. Some dark sediment. Aroma of dark soy sauce, molasses... my wife thought Worcestershire sauce. The smokiness and juniper are beautifully melded, and neither is aggressively apparent. Spicy, almost gingery tang; I thought perhaps it was an alcohol burn, but when I checked the ABV it was surprisingly low... so I guess this must be the influence of the juniper. If this were less than $10 a bottle, Id be drinking it regularly. As it stands, though, its going to be yet another great Special Occasion Beer.

Lovely deep brown color; large tan head that lasts a surprisingly long time. Spicy: cloves dissipating into bitter chocolate. For us non-Francophones, the missing article on the label suggests a regrettable false cognate: theres nothing terrible about this beer... unless you count the deceptively high alcohol content.

beer_brewer_name: Leinenkugel Brewing Company (Tenth & Blake Beer Co.)
review_blob: Bottle. Aroma suggests a high-quality soy sauce. Deep black-brown color; very modest deep brown head. Mouthfeel surprisingly light, and the 9.5% alcohol is scarcely noticeable. Taste a lovely balance of mild toffee sweetness and bitterness; suggestion of bitter chocolate in the aftertaste. I am sorely tempted to overindulge.
beer_name: Leinenkugels Big Eddy Russian Imperial Stout

review_blob: No head. No carbonation to speak of. Usually I dont mind floating chunks, but the utter stillness of the brew made me think of dirty water this time. Id like to make a wisecrack about "Puhti" being the sound I made spitting it out... but it really wasnt that unpleasant. Just not at all to my taste. Never, ever again.

If youve nothing better to drink on a hot day, make sure its cold; then aim it at the back of your tongue and drink it quickly. Drunk this way, it can be pretty refreshing. But do not stop to savor this beer, or youll get a mouthful of rotten corn (OK, I know theres supposed to be no actual corn in it, and Ive never actually tasted rotten corn... but thats my impression). Full disclosure: I live at sea level, so perhaps my 6-pack was suffering from reverse altitude sickness.

I fell in love with Shochu during my brief time in South Japan, so I was very curious about a beer matured in Shochu casks. The aroma is mildly fruity -- my first thought was peach, but thats not quite it (Ill probably sit bolt awake at three oclock this morning remembering what it is: "Aha! Lychee! It was lychee!" or some such nonsense). The color is deep orange, deepening still further to opaque orange-brown in the middle of the glass. Lots of tiny floaty bits. Thick yellowish head that lingers. Flavor has a mild citrusy tang to it. Slightly syrupy alcohol finish, more warming than aggressive. Different and much better than anything I was expecting.

Pours golden yellow. The head is perfunctory and doesnt last long (just like sex after marriage). But with its 6% alcohol (at least before they tampered with the recipe) and its bracing finish of bitter hops, Singha has a bit more character than its undistinguished appearance lets on. I used to be much more impressed by this beer when I was younger. I think that was because I always drank it in Thai restaurants along with Thai food, which as other reviewers have noted is a perfect match for the beer.

The label says "stout"; obviously it is not. It seems to be a mistranslation for "strong". And Strong it is! My bottle claimed 9% rather than 9.5%, so maybe I got an old bottle... but 9% is still a healthy wallop. aibo pours brownish-gold and cloudy, an appearance I found murky and unappetizing. Let me put it this way: if this stuff came out looking the same as it went in, Id call a doctor. But the beer was a bit more pleasant to drink than to look at. The alcohol isnt quite as overpowering as I thought it would be; and while its very sweet and yeasty, with a syrupy mouthfeel, its not quite as cloying as Uosto, which was the last Rinkukiai beer Id had.

First of all, though the back label claims this is a "stout beer", it is absolutely not a stout. I imagine this is a problem with translation: possibly they were looking for the English word for "Strong Beer", and someone (unacquainted with the actual product, and naturally thinking of Baltic porter, or Imperial Stout) could have suggested "stout". A quick look at an English dictionary would show that "stout" could mean "heavy-bodied", or "strong and full of character". Not realizing that these definitions applied to people and not to styles of beer, the Lithuanian Marketing Dept. went ahead with their label designs... at least thats my guess.

As for the beer? Unremarkable lager aroma. Pours clear golden yellow, not too pale, with a credible if short-lived attempt at a head. An initial malty fruitiness soon gives way to a yeasty sugar-syrup flavor. The hops fight valiantly to dry things out a little, but to no avail: the end notes are almost cloyingly sweet. It does hide its 8% alcohol reasonably well: I was thinking the ABV might be a little exaggerated, and then I discovered my nose was gone.

I thought there was a very surprising sweetish note in the aroma. It was present in the first sip, too -- a hint of some candyish, fruity flavor I cant quite place; more banana-y than corny, but... bananas not right, either. Its a little disconcerting. The color is a clear but uninteresting golden yellow, with a fizzy white head that flattens to nothing (and I mean NOTHING) very quickly. Mouthfeel is watery. Pleasant enough flavor to start out with, but by the last sip I felt like I was drinking old dishwater. My curiosity is sated.

Nice malty aroma. Pours a pleasant deep brown (as expected) with a white, quickly-dissipating head. Flavor is a good balance between malt and bitter hops. Enjoyable and very easily drinkable -- I will frequently drink this until I suddenly discover my legs are missing -- but not, in my opinion, a beer to linger over; concentrate on the flavors too long and a certain alcoholic acidity comes to the fore, something I find a little unpleasant. This has become my Old Reliable beer, the one I go back to when the other choices seem overwhelming... but then again,  I have an Old Brown Dog of my own, so perhaps Im biased.

Wow. Pours black as forever,with a thick brown head that lingers. Incipit is a complex burst of spicy florals. Mouthfeel is oily in the best sense. Has a gentle bitterness that doesnt really become noticeable until the finish... (just like sex!).

Pours black and opaque, with a deep brown head that dissipates quickly. Coffee is immediately apparent in the aroma (which for me is a good thing), but the taste is much subtler than the aroma would suggest. First sip promises a rich, toasty, chocolatey stout -- but the finish is pure dark-roast coffee. Its as though they found the perfect marriage of my 2 favorite beverages. If this were easier to find and less expensive, Id be drinking quite a lot of this.
